Inflation, in Europe, has skidded on food
Accelerated inflation, measured in the euro area, is mainly due to the rapid rise in food prices.
In November, price increases in the 13 euro area countries were higher than forecast, after an inflation rate of 2.6 per cent in October, annual inflation of 3.1 per cent was recorded, the European Community Statistics Office in Luxembourg said.
Official forecasts indicated only 3 percent, Bloomberg reported.
Unlike the US, UK and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not lowered the key interest rate by saying that falling interest rates, along with rising commodity prices and falling unemployment rates, would lead to the generation of an inflationary spiral.
The ECB would like to keep the inflation rate below but close to two percent.
According to one analyst, it is Catch 22 for the ECB: "it is necessary to deter" inflation so as not to have to intervene on this subject later.
In Germany, the inflation rate of 3.3 per cent is a record over the past twelve years and in Spain it has risen from 3.6 to 4.1.
Inflation in the euro area has taken off due to the rapid rise in food and energy prices.
The futures market for cereals has increased by 88 percent and the soybean price has also reached its highest value since 1973.
The price of food oil and dairy products also increased considerably in 2007.
This year, the global oil price rose 52 percent, and last month, a barrel of black gold cost nearly $100.
According to the ECB, in 2008 the inflation rate will rise from 2.1 this year to 2.5 per cent, but in 2009 it will fall to 1.9.
According to analysts, the 12-month inflation rate remains around 3 percent, however, over the next 3 to 4 months, the average annual rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, they expect the ECB to lower the key rate twice in 2008.
Gallup Reportedly Reported a Government Crisis
