Auchan is the most expensive, Tesco has increased its prices by almost twenty percent
The hypermarkets in the Buda<0xC3><0xB6>rs trade triangle maintained the average price increase of 16 per cent last year, although this year the VAT rate has not increased.
Article by Napi Gazdas<0xC3><0xA1>g (Daily Economy)
This year, in the commercial triangle of Buda<0xC3><0xB6>rs, the usual daily Christmas Basket also increased by an average of 16 percent, a value increase well above a thousand forints being displayed in all hypermarkets.
Prices, “which had already soared” in grocery stores last December, no longer rose sharply compared to the previous high base.
Nevertheless, consumers are obviously shocked to see that items bought well below nine thousand forints last year now cost more than ten thousand forints.
The Daily Basket in the surveyed hypermarkets exceeded by 91 forints, at least, the psychological threshold of ten thousand forints.
And the highest value of the basket was 10,573 forints.
(In 2003, this figure was 6,800 forints.)
Prices of Unicum and live fish remained close to last year's level, however prices of turkey net, walnut and poppy have risen sharply.
In stores, the price of flour and bread followed data from the KSH (Central Institute of Statistics) but, at Auchan, we found bread from one kilo to only 139 forints.
The competition did not lower the price of the product below 200 forints.
It was surprising to see, also in this hypermarket, that the price of the two-liter bottle of Coca-Cola was below 200 forints, so it only cost 257 forints per bottle.
Only this year, in terms of Daily Basket, Auchan was the most expensive and Cora the cheapest.
According to our calculations, Cora increased the price of his daily Basket by 15 percent while Tesco and Auchan increased them by about 18 and 18 percent respectively.
By comparing the most expensive basket of last year and the cheapest basket of this year, we see a difference of 12 percent while the difference between the cheapest one of last year and the most expensive one of this year is 21 percent.
Prices increased by an average of 1,480 forints.
Last year, prices increased by an average of 1,206 forints, while knowing that the impact of the increase in the VAT rate was already noticeable in last year's Christmas prices.
This process has puzzled trade, with hypermarkets unable to visibly determine what margin to apply to products as they were unable to predict the impact of price change on consumption.
(If a trader miscalculates the rotation of a product, he risks losing a large profit on the margin adapted to the intensity of the trade.)
Due to the change in the VAT rate, the increase in the prices of the Daily Basket has evolved so excessively that the most expensive basket was higher than the value of 1 720 forints in 2006, while the difference between the cheapest baskets was only 844 forints.
This year, the difference was not so excessive since the value of the most expensive basket was higher by 1,630 forints than last year and the cheapest prices increased by 1,284 forints as well.
As we approached the two Christmas seasons, we saw a catastrophic increase in prices, in less than 20 months the prices of everyday consumer goods increased by more than 30 percent in hypermarkets.
(This does not necessarily confirm KSH data: for some essential foods, the Institute of Statistics found a price increase of more than 30 per cent in 12 months.
This is the case, for example, of flour and egg.)
According to the Daily Basket of the latter, this seems almost absurd since the price level of this product, already well-priced last year, has increased by barely more than 10 percent compared to the base.
According to the indices, the flour suppliers occupy a stronger position than the egg suppliers because they have managed to get the brutal increase in prices also accepted by the multinationals.
In the commercial gold triangle, hypermarkets do not complain, they constantly record good years.
According to our experiences, the majority of customers no longer look at prices in the three hypermarkets visited.
They buy everything in quantity, they take long-preserved foods by pallets.
On Wednesday morning, important queues formed at the cash registers of the three hypermarkets as the number of customers increased sharply.
However, according to our information, the turnover is less important in the province, many multinationals complain to the survey companies that they do not even reach the expected turnover, not only for food but also for sustainable consumer items.
Many Hospitals Are Saving on Disinfectants
This year, more than a thousand infections, mainly caused by improper use of antibiotics, have been registered in hospitals.
The hygienic conditions of hospitals, the insufficient number of beds, the overcrowding of medical staff do not help to block infections, says the chief physician of the National Centre of Epidemiology.
Many hospitals are also saving on disinfectants.
Not long ago an MRSA infection was diagnosed at the traumatology department of J<0xC3><0xA1>nos Hospital.
The antibiotic-resistant bacterium was detected on a hospitalized man following a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
At the beginning of the year, a similar infection occurred in the same place.
The victim of a serious car accident left the hospital but soon after he had to return due to an MRSA infection and, since then, doctors have not been able to do a major operation on him because of the bacteria in his body.
As of December 10 this year, 1,094 hospital infections generated by a multidrug-resistant pathogen have been reported to the National Nosocomial Surveillance System, said Karolina B<0xC3><0xB6>r<0xC3><0xB6>cz, chief physician at the National Centre for Epidemiology.
That is the number of infections caused by a multidrug-resistant pathogen that has actually been registered in hospitals and for the rest we have no information.
About two-thirds of infections (683 infections) were caused by MRSA, i.e. methicillin-oxacillin-resistant staphylococcus aureus.
One-third of people carry Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacteria in their noses without developing a disease.
Infections caused by SA (such as angina, tonsillitis, skin infections, traumatic infections) respond well to antibiotics, they are easily curable.
However, if antibiotics are used excessively or inappropriately, the bacterium, which reacts well to antibiotics, will develop a well-resistant bacterium that will proliferate rapidly in poor hospital conditions.
In case of temporary or prolonged malfunction of the immune system, this bacterium can cause serious hospital infections, such as a traumatic infection or septicemia, on the elderly, patients with low weight or with a weakened organism.
According to the medical director of the J<0xC3><0xA1>nos hospital, there is nothing special in MRSA infections, these infections are part of the daily life of hospitals.
Above all, we should not confuse the infection with the epidemic, we do not find MRSA only where we do not look for them, said Tibor Nyulasi.
SAs are resistant to antibiotics.
“These patients are isolated, the care staff wear rubber gloves and protective masks and we have appropriate antibiotics to treat them,” said Tibor Nyulasi.
A priori, hospitalized patients are examined if they are carriers of MRSA, however, infection cannot always be avoided.
Sampling is not in fashion
The vast majority of infections caused by MRSA could be prevented but the current conditions and circumstances are not favorable, in Hungarian hospitals, to prevent the development and proliferation of multidrug-resistant pathogens, says Karolina B<0xC3><0xB6>r<0xC3><0xB6>cz.
As this infection is manifested mainly in hospitals and nursing homes, hospitals should monitor hospitalized patients and immediately isolate patients with MRSA.
However, microbiological sampling is not fashionable in Hungarian hospitals.
It should be noted that the National Social Security Fund does not fund these reviews.
Most cases only occur if the MRSA infection is detectable on the patient, the chief physician of the epidemiology center said.
The European Union has strong recommendations on the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine and there are also Hungarian guidelines for the healing of certain infections and syndromes.
Efforts must be made to ensure that antibiotic therapy is targeted, i.e. microbiological examinations should be performed to prevent drug resistance, but hospitals do not always take this into account.
Microbiological sampling is even rarer in outpatient and basic care, Karolina B<0xC3><0xB6>r<0xC3><0xB6>cz said.
Many Hospitals Are Saving on Disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that MRSA proliferates from one patient to another most often through medical personnel.
It is therefore essential to wash your hands, put on gloves and protective masks, but important gaps are also detected in hospitals in this area.
MRSAs proliferate by infection transmitted by inhalation of droplets and by contact. However, due to conditions in Hungarian hospitals, the infected patient cannot always be isolated.
In addition, the rooms are often full, the beds are often too close to each other while in terms of epidemic, patients should be away from each other by at least 1.5 meters.
Unfortunately, we also find that hospitals, in a difficult financial situation, save money on disinfectants, they lack nurses, there are many patients, so the risk of contamination is even greater, Karolina B<0xC3><0xB6>r<0xC3><0xB6>cz said.
According to Karolina B<0xC3><0xB6>r<0xC3><0xB6>cz, in hospitals or preventive measures are respected, the number of infections is lower demonstrably or the proliferation of the pathogen can be blocked.
Government project against MRSA
The treatment of MRSA infection is an exorbitant expense for social security funds, which is why we are fighting this infection everywhere.
In England, for example, the government has established a program to prevent or reduce the incidence of MRSA.
According to published data, this program is effective and MRSA infections show a decreasing trend in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) has identified as its priorities the prevention of the incidence of multidrug-resistant pathogens (such as MRSA) as well as the prevention of hospital infections caused by these pathogens.
The Commissioner, the author of a fatal accident, was not in a state of intoxication
The official statement regarding the fatal accident caused by the Commissioner of the 22nd arrondissement was made.
It can be excluded that the commissioner of the 22nd arrondissement, who has since resigned from his post, who crushed a pedestrian by causing his death last Tuesday, would have led in a state of drunkenness or stupor, said Attila Morvai, spokesman for the public ministry of the capital after the relative finding was established.
