Bulgaria, a haven for the EU real estate market
The evolution of the Bulgarian real estate market is spectacular, the attention of the whole of Europe is turned to this country of the Balkans little mentioned in the past.
What, or who bought in this EU market that is always the cheapest but will quickly become expensive?
Analysis of the Bulgarian division of Re/Max.
Currently, in real estate, Bulgaria is undoubtedly the most popular destination in Eastern Europe with its ski apartments and cheap seaside houses.
In the mountains, the most popular regions are Bansko, Borovec, Pamprovo and Vitosa and, by the sea, Albena, the "Golden Sands", the "Sun Coast", the ancient Sozopol and Nessebar but they are increasingly looking for a building in the Kavarna and Balcik region as well.
According to analysts of Re/Max Bulgaria, sooner or later, the central region of the country, namely Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, Triavna, will also awaken the interest of investors and they are also more and more numerous to buy in the very cheap corner of Russia.
Sofia, the capital, offers attractive opportunities as well, with retail and office space promising the highest depreciation rate.
Bulgaria is on the best track to become one of the most attractive golf paradises in Europe and thus be a priority destination, after the summer season and the winter season, also in the other two seasons of the year.
More vigilant investors are already buying in large numbers, for example in the Bansko area.
According to analysts, people buying a building in Bulgaria are looking at the same time to change their lives, their way of life.
Most of the buyers are English but others come from France, Belgium, Spain and more and more from Romania.
The Maltese and Cypriot investors are also present. On the Black Sea coast and in the most famous ski resorts, we traditionally meet many Russian buyers.
Foreign buyers are divided into three groups, says Georgy Jankov, Regional Director of Re/Max Bulgaria.
People who intend to settle buy renovated buildings, at a price ranging from 50 to 100 thousand euros, or old dilapidated houses, at a price ranging from 5 to 15 thousand euros, which are then renovated.
The criteria are easy access and communication possibilities, proximity to a large city, shops and in general that of the local doctor.
The second group includes buyers of secondary residences (since last December, Bulgaria is listed among the top 10 holiday destinations in Germany).
The third group is made up of commercial investors who buy in the hope of achieving a medium- or long-term gain.
The price of the capital's buildings is constantly increasing due to an increasing demand.
In the European Union, real estate prices are the lowest in Bulgaria. However, in the last 5 years, they have increased by 21 percent each year.
The increase in real estate prices is essentially greater than the increase in wages.
Fodor and the Six Percent Hungarians
According to the communication of G<0xC3><0xA1>bor Fodor, Minister of Environment and Water, the meetings of the professionals end on Tuesday, however, on Wednesday, after the official opening, the negotiations of the ministers on the international climate regime after 2012 will continue.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries around the world will discuss the Bali Roadmap, which is supposed to define the efforts to be made after the emission reduction period defined by the Kyoto Protocol until 2012.
At the moment, there are lively discussions on this issue between developing countries and developed countries.
The United States also reported that, for the time being, they did not want to discuss exact figures, although they were ready to sign an agreement on reducing, by 2020, greenhouse gas emissions by 25 to 40 percent compared to the 1990 level.
Another important topic of the conference is whether developed countries, apart from reducing emissions, are committed to providing financial and technological assistance to countries in need.
An agreement was also signed on aid to be provided to developing countries.
The aid fund defined by the Kyoto Protocol will be managed by a board of directors composed of 16 members, probably within the framework of the UN Global Environment Facility (GEF), Piac és Profit (Market and Profit) has announced.
Six percent of Hungary
On behalf of Hungary, G<0xC3><0xA1>bor Fodor, Minister of the Environment and Waters, confirms the EU's ambition to maintain its role as an admiral ship in global efforts to protect the climate and encourage the signing of the new international agreement by 2009.
The minister explained that the EU was committed to reducing its greenhouse gas emissions by 20 percent by 2020 compared to the level reached in 1990, regardless of the success of the signing of the “After 2012 Agreement”, and was ready to reduce them by up to 30 percent if other major regions of the world and/or developing countries were also ready to take their adaptations.
G<0xC3><0xA1>bor Fodor recalled that in 1997, the countries that signed the Kyoto Protocol had been aiming for a total reduction of 5.2 per cent and that the total of the 15 EU members at that time had made a commitment of 8 per cent less.
Hungary has made a commitment to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 6 per cent compared to the level of the period between 1985 and 1987, our country will fulfill its commitment, the press release of the Ministry of the Environment recalls.
The issue is great in Bali because the long-term international agreement on climate policy must be put in place within the two-year timeframe that the new UN treaty will get, otherwise the entry into force of the agreement would certainly be postponed after 2012. In this case, the reduction commitments below the values provided in the Kyoto Protocol would not be immediately followed by a new international reduction system.
The reduction in emissions would be delayed and the increase in the average temperature of the Earth by more than 2 degrees Celsius could no longer be avoided which, according to scientists, would have extremely serious and irreversible consequences.
The British army recruits on YouTube
On the video-sharing site, units of the British Army communicate recordings made during its operations in Iraq and Afghanistan in order to become popular.
First, it is the British Air Force (RAF) that has been passionate about YouTube: special units in Afghanistan have been uploading video footage of operations against the Taliban since March 2006, the BBC announced.
These recordings, taken using miniature cameras mounted on the helmet, are checked at the Air Force Operations Headquarters in Kandahar and are then transferred to London or the compatriots upload them to the Internet.
The political message is essential
Air force soldiers have already passed 139 sequences on the net through this route and their "chain" has been watched by more than 75,000 people.
The British Ministry of Defence registered as Defence Headquarters in the spring of 2007 and provides videos on operations in Iraq and Afghanistan while the Commonwealth Office and the International Peacekeeping Forces in Iraq (IMF) also have their own YouTube channels.
Mission in Afghanistan
According to the initial objective of the air force, the videos were passed on the net to recruit. According to the Ministry of Defence, they were also used to make known to the general public the real objectives of the presence of the army abroad.
The propaganda published by this channel costs practically nothing compared to the usual recruitment advertisements passed on television, according to a statement to the BBC Gordon Mackenzie, a defence consultant, but it also inevitably carries a political message since it justifies in a special form the merits of the military operations decided by the government.
The Americans made a game.
The army is bothered because, apart from the carefully composed and censored videos, amateur videos are passed on the sharing site that also present, for example, the death of soldiers: in the "official" propaganda films, a little hypocritical, officers do not avoid talking about losses but they never present the fighting side.
In fact, many videos had already been posted showing the areas of operations in Iraq and Afghanistan that were being carried out on a real mission, but the British army has been packing up to upload these videos only recently.
Americans do the recruiting a little differently using the free downloadable America's Army shooting game. In this game the player can put himself directly in the place of soldiers as part of a more or less real simulation.
