The party is not marked in red everywhere
In Hungary, the law defines exactly the days of the holiday and, around the holidays, it has become common to reorganize the working days whose number will decrease next year.
The holidays are not uniform in the EU and the United States either.
Hungarian legislation distinguishes national and state holidays as well as rest days.
Rest days are often linked to religious holidays or important historical events.
In Hungary, we celebrate the new year, the last day of the year that ends and the first day of the new year are also days of rest, the latter all the more so so that the alarm clocks can rest quietly.
In addition, in a year, we have a total of eleven holidays marked in red.
March 15 is a national holiday, commemorating the 1848 revolution, as is October 23 which is also the day commemorating the 1956 revolution.
On August 20, we celebrate the constitution of our state, on May 1 is the Labor Day and on November 1 and 2, we remember members of our family and our deceased friends.
In addition, we have two days at Easter, at Pentecost and at Christmas.
The days of our state, national or even religious holidays rarely fall on a weekend, according to the calendar, it has become common to reorganize the working days in cases where there is only one working day left before or after the holiday marked in red.
It is true that we pay the price of extended weekends by working or going to school on the Saturday before the extended weekend.
For many years, the Minister of Labour has been making special regulations for days before or after the holidays.
The law extends to all employers and all their employees, to civil servants and to persons working in the public service.
It does not apply, however, to service societies, to institutions that are constantly in service, by their vocation, and also to days of rest.
This year, working days will be changed only around the end of the year holidays: from December 24, life stops almost all over the country because according to experiences most people do rather overtime or take holidays that they have saved for these purposes to be able to spend the days between Christmas and New Year's Day at home.
Next year many holidays fall in the middle or end of the week, so there will be fewer changes in the level of working days compared to this year.
The schedule will be reorganized for the first time around Labor Day to allow employees to stay at home for four days in a row.
Saturday 25 April will be a working day to have a rest day on Friday 2 May.
Another change is planned for October 23: Saturday, October 18 will be a working day replacing Friday, October 24.
On the other hand, next year, the end of the year is announced under the sign of the holidays because from December 24, everyone will take a non-stop break even if the day of the new year falls on a Wednesday.
Six futile things that can horribly annoy colleagues
Emails that we forget to send, voice messages that we never receive, innocent lies that almost annoy us more: these are things that “beautify” the daily life of a workplace.
The question is whether we get used to these troubles or whether we rise to the challenge and consciously avoid ambiguous situations, causing trouble to others.
Examples.
