Banks want to solve the crisis
The Federal Reserve Bank of the United States, the European Central Bank and the British, Swiss and Canadian central banks have decided to fight together the crisis of the financial markets.
More than one hundred billion dollars will be placed in the money markets through auctions.
It will be for the banks to sell, through an auction system, the interest rates at which they are willing to borrow money.
As an example, the US Fed will auction off $40 billion and provide $24 billion to the European and Swiss central banks.
This is the first time since the attacks of 11 September that the central banks of individual states have decided to take action on this concerted point, aimed at preventing or even reducing the effects of the financial crisis.
“This approach tends to address the major problems of the economy, namely the growing lack of free capital that banks could lend,” writes Bernard Baumohl of the consulting firm Economic Outlook Group in his report to clients.
“The concerted action of the central banks has reduced the likelihood of a U.S. recession from 65 percent to about 50 percent,” Baumohl added in his report.
Banks have already lost $60 billion due to non-repayable loans, especially in the United States.
Analysts expect more losses in the billions.
“If the central banks have chosen this approach, it’s that they have to really understand what can still happen,” said Amro Kieran Davies, chief economist at ABN.
“It seems that the situation is really bad,” he adds.
Central banks fear that if banks themselves have difficult access to loans, they will lend more to their customers.
This would reduce consumption and plunge the U.S. economy into a recession that could affect global economic growth.
The central banks made this choice after the London interbank rate, called LIBOR, used to borrow on the interbank market, was not brought down.
This meant that banks were still concerned about mutual borrowing, despite the fact that the US, Canadian and English central banks had repeatedly lowered their interest rates during the fall.
"This will have the same effect as a further drop in interest rates," Greg Salvaggio of Tempus Consulting told Reuters.
Some analysts do not believe that the move by the central banks will help to ward off the crisis, since it does not solve the main problem that is the fall of the real estate market in the United States.
