Cuba, the most beautiful island in the Caribbean
For visitors, it is truly an island of freedom.
Everything you expect from your vacation can be accomplished if you make a good choice.
Golden and white beaches like snow, high waves or a calm sea like a pond.
Palm trees and all inclusive with servers offering you on the beach a pizza, ice cream or intoxicating cocktails.
Kitesurfing, golf and roulette.
On the islands of the Caribbean Sea, you will not find this list only in its entirety, but enriched.
Now, there is only one island on which you will find much more and it is Cuba, the largest and most beautiful island in the Greater Antilles.
At the time of the Spanish, Cuba had been the bastion of their invasion of America.
Christopher Columbus called it the most beautiful place the human eye has ever seen.
Havana became the repository and place of transhipment of the treasures that the Spaniards had stolen and transported to Europe.
Then came the American era.
The Hotel Nacional was built in the early 20's.
It was Lucky Luciano, one of the leaders of the American mafia, who built it, since everything that was a crime in the United States (especially under prohibition) was admitted and supported in Cuba: drugs, gambling, prostitution.
Among his clients were, among others,
Winston Churchill, Ava Gardner, Frank Sinatra.
In Havana, high-rise buildings grew and cars, belonging to the cult symbols of the 50's of the last century, circulated on the wide boulevards.
Ernest Hemingway bought a property in San Francisco de Paula, near Havana, and, in Coj<0xC3><0xAD>mar, he had his yacht.
The stars of the show business and politicians from all over America left their signatures on the walls of the Bodeguita del Medio.
What about today?
You can leave your autograph on the walls of Havana’s Bodeguita.
In the bar of the Nacional hotel, a luxury hotel, you will be mixed the cocktail of your choice.
And these cult cars still circulate in Havana, since the jigoulis and fiats once imported have long since, in such a salty and wet climate, rotten.
Although Havana, especially the oldest part, is significantly decrepit, nowhere else in the vicinity there are as many splendid colonial monuments as there are precisely there.
Other places become more beautiful, for example Trinidad.
Since tourism brings money if necessary, its development has the green light.
Over the past fifteen years, new hotels have grown not only in Havana, but especially in Varader, on the coast of Holgu<0xC3><0xAD>n province, and also on small islands such as Cayo Coco, Cayo Guillermo and others.
Cuba still offers a fantasy that is unique in the world and that will be appreciated especially by lovers of small trains.
The cane had come back from the plantations spread in the sweet shops on a narrow track by small steam and motor trains.
Their rolling stock has not been renewed for decades and this is how you can see on the go small locomotives whose contemporaries are elsewhere only in museums.
Where to direct his steps?
The majority of visitors do not miss the most famous places.
So there is no need to write long about Varadero or Havana.
Otherwise remember that in the property of Hemingway, already mentioned, there is a museum and that the one who likes this writer should not miss the visit.
The Vi<0xC5><0x88>ales Valley to the west of the island is one of the most picturesque corners of Cuba.
Exuberant vegetation grows there on a limestone soil.
Mogotes, calcareous balloons, and rocks rise in candlesticks from the bottom of the valley, and, with fertile earth caught in their bowels, even its rotten rocks are covered with a very dense vegetal carpet.
The valley is probably the place where the best quality Cuban tobacco is grown.
You will be able to meet the final form of this product if you visit one of the cigar factories in Havana.
Someone may also find it interesting that this is where Major Zeman's Chilean episode was filmed.
Trinidad
An ancient city founded shortly after the Spanish colonized the island.
It is the market of the slave trade and that of sugar that have brought it glory and wealth.
The wealth has been embodied in the beauty and character of the city-window of this small town.
The colonial Spanish architecture, greatly influenced by the later French settlers, has hardly changed over the course of four centuries.
Trinidad, located between the sea and the mountain massif Escambray, is a place so far apart that even in the 50's of the last century, there was no road that would connect this region with the rest of the country.
This isolation allowed him to stay away.
We didn't build anything, and that's why we didn't demolish anything either, everyone just had a roof over their head.
If you have more time in Trinidad than an afternoon, then it is worth going to see also interesting places in the vicinity, such as Playa Anc<0xC3><0xB3>n beach or the Valley of Sweets.
Then, in the evening, it is customary to go to the Casa de la M<0xC3><0xBA>sica, which is animated after sunset and where the music is deafening only in the early morning.
Baracoa
Some refer to this village located in the far east of Cuba as the most beautiful on the island.
This opinion is certainly already influenced by the path that leads to it.
The two roads that lead from Guant<0xC3><0xA1>namo must cross high and rugged mountains and cross an almost unmarked landscape of human activity.
UNESCO has inscribed Cuba’s eastern shelf, thanks to its intact landscape, on the World Heritage list.
The best chocolate is made there, in the church, there is the cross of Christopher Columbus (in reality, it was born about a hundred years after the journey to Columbus) and from the hill where the old castle and the current hotel El Castillo, you can see several mountains table, the most famous of which is El Yunque.
On the subject of coffee, rum, cigars, the Sierra Maestra mountain massif, the Bay of Pigs and Isla de Pinos, the Tropicana cabaret, the sanctuary of the patron saint of Cuba Caridad del Cobre, the Santeria, the African religions practiced by the descendants of former slaves, a page full of all this could be filled.
But, as they say, it’s better to see it once.
In Afghanistan, allies are passive, say U.S.
The lack of troops and necessary equipment, according to the United States, influences the course of the mission in Afghanistan.
According to Defense Minister Robert Gates, NATO should outline a concrete plan for the coming years.
The mission in Afghanistan is not going as it should, the representatives of countries that have troops in the southern part of the country agreed in Edinburgh, Scotland.
In addition to the growing opposition from the Taliban movement, the eight states involved today also discuss future plans and the coordination of the allies.
While the U.S. this week called through Defense Minister Robert Gates for NATO troops to greater activity, Britain sees as a priority the strengthening of the Afghan government's authority and the intensification of development aid.
“The evolution in Afghanistan is perceptible, but military power can only be part of the solution.
The other being to allow the inhabitants to start a new development of the economy and security themselves," Defence Minister Des Browne told the BBC.
Ninety per cent
The activity of the Afghan insurgents is, according to U.S. military data, the most intense in the last five years.
The number of violent actions increased by 27 percent compared to last year, to 60 percent in Helmand province, located in the south of the country.
NATO countries have about 40,000 troops in Afghanistan, nearly a quarter of them in the southern part.
However, according to the United States, the allies have reached their absolute limit both in the organization and in the equipment of the troops.
In concrete terms, they are asking for other helicopters, soldiers and experts to train Afghan troops.
“We will have to think seriously about the concrete goals for the coming period, as well as how to achieve them,” Gates said.
NATO Secretary General Jaap de Hoop made similar remarks today.
“I’m not happy with what we have on the ground and in the air in Afghanistan.
We have about ninety percent of the soldiers and equipment we would need, and that’s not enough,” De Hoop told Reuters at the end of talks with the Japanese government in Tokyo that lasted three days.
Who is passive
In recent months, there have also been conflicts among the countries involved in the issue of whether all the allies are actually doing their best in Afghanistan.
For example, Germany has been criticized for its passivity.
"The Germans have a relatively large representation in Afghanistan.
But they are engaged in areas where violence is minimal, so the combat requirements they are subject to are not as stringent as those in the southern and eastern parts of the country where we operate,” Gates said.
The British tabloid Sun called the German soldiers lazy this week.
“Afghan idlers discovered: Germans play while ours fight,” Sun wrote in a document supplemented by photos of German soldiers playing table tennis.
The German newspaper Bild went on the counter-attack by posting the photo of a British troop during a rugby match in the southern part of Afghanistan.
Government debt to rise to one trillion in 2009
The burden of a state debt exceeding 84,000 crowns is on each Czech Republic.
Total debt rose at the end of September to 842.7 billion kroner.
The government had planned to borrow 159.2 billion kroner this year.
Thanks to a better-than-expected evolution of the state budget savings, the ministry has reduced the planned amount to 152.8 billion kroner.
The debt of the State of the Czech Republic rose towards the end of September to 842.7 billion crowns.
During the nine months of this year it has therefore increased by 40.2 billion crowns.
However, as of June, it has decreased by 13.4 billion kroner.
Today, the Ministry of Finance has confirmed its data on the state's debt dating back to early October.
The burden of a debt exceeding 84,000 crowns falls on each Czech Republic.
During the whole of last year, the state owed more than 111 billion crowns.
"At the moment, it seems that, thanks to a smaller deficit planned for next year, we could cross the border by a trillion crowns only in 2009.
Next year, the debt is expected to be between 900 billion and one trillion crowns," Patria Finance analyst David Marek told iHNed.cz.
Next Finance analyst Vladim<0xC3><0xAD>r Picor’s prediction is similar: “We could exceed a trillion by the end of 2009.
The exact date will depend on the next budget that is not yet known.
If it turns out that the situation on the political scene is changing, that politicians are ready to save more, the date could be pushed back to 2010.
But I don’t expect this change,” he said.
Debts are growing
The debt of the state is constituted by the debts of the central government and it is generated mainly by the accumulation of deficits of the state budget.
State debt is financed by treasury bonds, bonds, direct loans or, for example, loans to the European Investment Bank.
The state's domestic debt has so far increased this year from 38.5 billion to 719.4 billion kroner.
The state’s external debt has so far increased this year from 1.7 billion kroner to 123.3 billion kroner.
The debt of the state called negotiable reached 803.3 billion kroner at the end of September and from June it decreased by 13.7 billion kroner.
The average debt requirement for the state was 6.5 years.
“Total debt has increased year-on-year from the first to the third half of 13 percent, which is, given the current good health of the economy, a much too high figure.
Interestingly, the increase is mainly generated by the bonds where it reaches 20 percent.
It is bad that the debt is growing, but on the other hand it indicates that there will be material to negotiate when the pension reform comes,” Pikora said.
Better than we expected
It follows from the government's strategy of financing and managing the state's debt for 2007 that the government had planned to borrow 159.2 billion kroner this year.
However, at the beginning of September, thanks to a better-than-expected change in the economy of the state budget, the Ministry reduced the planned amount to 152.8 billion crowns.
The sum is essentially constituted by the deficit of the state budget, which is clearly going to reach 76 billion crowns this year, instead of the 91.3 billion crowns originally planned.
Next, these are the maximum sources planned for the Czech Consolidation Agency, namely 13.3 billion crowns, the reserve of 10 billion crowns for the payment of pensions, the financing of state pension securities for 43 billion crowns and the repayments of loans from the European Investment Bank amounting to 1.8 billion crowns.
She appeared today in court in Khartoum for naming a teddy bear
The British teacher tried in Sudan for insulting Islam was sentenced Thursday night by a Khartoum court to 15 days in prison and deportation, her lawyer said.
The British woman was accused of letting students aged 6 to 7 give the name of Muhammad to a teddy bear while any depiction of the prophet of Islam is illegal.
She was liable to a whipping penalty.
The 54-year-old British teacher at Unity High School in Khartoum, Sudan, was arrested on Sunday at her home and charged with violating Islam and sedition under section 125 of the Sudanese Penal Code, following several complaints from parents of students to the Sudanese Ministry of Education.
The story actually dates back to September, when this teacher asked her students, aged 6/7, to choose a name for the teddy bear in the class.
“Eight names come out of the children’s mouths, including Hassan, Abdullah and Mohammed,” said school principal Robert Boulos.
Finally, after a vote in the class, 20 out of 23 children chose Mohamed as their preferred first name.
Mohamed is of course the name of the Muslim prophet, but above all a very common name in Sudan.
The children then made a book for the class with the picture of the bear followed by the legend “My name is Mohamed”.
The bear itself did not bear any label with that name, but the problem is simply that of the depiction of the prophet considered an insult to Islam.
One of Gillian Gibbons’ Muslim colleagues, a teacher at the same school in Sudan, said he knew her well and that she would never have done anything that could be insulting to a religious faith, “I just regret that she asked the children to vote for a name,” he said.
Opinion shared by many of the teacher's students who describe her as "very attentive to her students" and "who never talks about religion in class".
Recall that the name Mohamed is also the second most given name in Britain, it is written in English in 14 different ways.
This name often chosen by Muslim families is a way of honoring the prophet (often given to the first child of a family).
But what are the rules regarding the use of this name?
Can you give it to a toy?
It is, of course, a question of interpretation.
