After more than 60 years of confidentiality, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which trace the fate of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are freely accessible.
The 47 million archival documents, stored on 27 km of linear in Bad Arolsen (Hesse), were up to now only available for "humanitarian" purposes, that is, individually and nominally, at the request of an ex-victim or his rightholders.
The eleven states in charge of their management - including Germany, France, Israel and the United States - agreed in May 2006 to open them to researchers and historians.
The process of ratification of this agreement by all States having been completed, the opening has been effective since yesterday.
Sensitive Information
Historians’ access to Bad Arolsen will allow them to conduct research “in particular on the displacement of prisoners, the population of the camps and the state of health of forced workers,” explains Reto Meistern, the director of these archives managed by the International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC).
Until recently, several States, including Germany, opposed the opening to the public of these nomination documents, due to the sensitive nature of certain information.
Such as the alleged homosexuality or mental disability of some victims of deportation.
The records of the concentration camps or arrest warrants established by the Gestapo had been compiled after the war for a practical purpose: to find the civilians deported or subjected to forced labour and, possibly, to provide them with evidence of their detention, in order to pave the way for their compensation.
Even today in Bad Arolsen, more than 300 permanent employees process tens of thousands of individual applications.
However, for some of the scientific community, access to Bad Arolsen is of limited interest.
