The Mifid, which amends the Securities Market Act, involves the modernization of financial markets, while strengthening investor protection, improving the powers of the leaders of the National Securities Market Commission (CNMV) and promoting cooperation between the various leaders of the European Union.
The new regulation will allow financial advisory services to be provided for specialized social reasons as well as to individuals or legal entities and creates a new type of financial advisory services (ESIS), financial advisory companies (AFI), which merge with securities companies, securities agencies and portfolio management companies.
In addition, it increases the number of systems for the execution of transactions on financial instruments, so that it is possible to add to regulated secondary markets multilateral trading systems and order internationalization systems, which face competition from current stock exchange managers.
The Act also requires investment services firms to disclose to the market information on key aspects of their business profile, risk exposure and risk management forms and requires them to keep a record of all the operations they carry out, to facilitate control by the CNMV.
In passing through the Congressional Economic Commission, several amendments have been added, one of which highlights that securitized debt will be considered a "complex" financial instrument given its high risk to the investor, which has proven itself with what happened with the debt of high-risk U.S. mortgages (subprime).
