The warning from the Auditor General, Robert Black, came after a foreign doctor working in Scotland was involved in the attack at Glasgow Airport in June.
Mr. Black also expressed concern that the Scottish Ministry of Health did not have any specific data on the number of overseas employees.
His report nonetheless highlighted other critical controls, which were properly performed on a sample of employees from five health authorities.
The Auditor General carried out checks on extra-community staff following the Glasgow airport attack.
Bilal Addullah, 28, an Iraqi doctor in the Royal Alexandra Hospital in Paisley, was arrested at the airport after dark with his jeep, in the gates of the main terminal.
He was one of three doctors who were filmed at the Old Bailey in October as he was suspected of being involved in various car bombing attempts in the UK.
The Ministry of Health will have to carry out pre-employment checks on overseas staff, to be sure of the validity of their qualifications, experiences, and work permits for the UK.
Although the Scottish Ministry of Health uses the Scottish Disclosure to carry out checks on previous criminal records, the agency has no right to obtain such information outside of the UK.
Among the many warnings, the Auditor General's report now states that committees are required to confront the Office of Criminal Records Control, thus allowing employers to undertake checks on various countries.
“Although we have found that certain information regarding staff has been verified, this is not done every time,” the report states.
Mr. Black said that the Scottish Ministry of Health carries out most of the pre-employment checks it would do itself, but he also added: "Our report highlights aspects where the system can be improved to ensure that adequate information on certain overseas staff members is available to health services.
Peter Terry, president of BMA Scotland, said it was "extremely unlikely" that pre-employment checks could identify employees who could commit future terrorist acts.
"The report suggests that the pre-employment checks currently being carried out are working well in the Scottish health system and that it is not certain that these warnings could bring any added value."
The Scottish health authorities have said they employ 1,161 people overseas, mostly doctors and nurses.
But the Auditor General pointed out that these figures certainly need to be revised upwards, in part because of the problems of identifying staff with fixed-term contracts, who might or might not choose to remain in our country.
The investigation has shown that the current control procedures of the health authorities in Ayrshire and Arran, Grampian, Greater Glasgow and Clyde, Lanarkshire, and Lothian, are quite adequate.
These checks are carried out on passports, work permits and qualifications.
The Government of Scotland is currently reviewing its policy and system of pre-employment controls for overseas staff in the health service.
Health Secretary Nicola Sturgeon said: “I was excited to do this work following the terrorist attack at Glasgow Airport.
She added that the Scottish Government, allied to the health committees, would carefully consider the warnings set out in the report to be published next month, and would commit to ensuring better execution of the recently updated pre-employment controls, which are valid for all employees, including overseas employees.
