With "The Hunting Party" and "Killing Peace", two films again tackle the Balkan War.
But they both don’t convince.
Either the projects are based too much on action and on the exchanges of senseless shots or on the contrary they are too tearful.
Here, even Richard Gere in "The Hunting Party" can't help.
The good news first: Karadzic and Mladic are still hiding in the Balkan mountains, but it is precisely there, in the most gloomy hinterland of the Bosnian war, that actor Richard Gere is found.
We had lastly lost sight of the most beautiful man of the eighties, because far too many cute and futile roles in women's sentimental films and far too many press conferences on the theme of Buddhism delighted him with the desire to show himself.
Today Richard Gere is suddenly the most important argument to watch anyway "The Hunting Party" - when the hunter becomes the hunted (why should today's films be as long and confusing as collective agreements of locomotive drivers?)
