But despite this asset, "The Hunting Party" continues together with the German production "Killing Peace", which also comes out this week, the endless series of films missed about the Balkan war.
The film is about two German soldiers in Kosovo (Adrian Topol, Max Riemelt), who rescue a Serb from the Kosovo snipers, in which one of the two falls in love quickly.
Although it is welcome that here Serbs are for once not presented as the sole causes of all ills, this film as flat as a telefilm gets lost far too quickly in the action and exchanges of senseless shots.
This remains a kind of "Alarm for Cobra 11" without highway but with a war in place.
On the contrary, we can examine in the perfect example of "The Hunting Party", why at bottom there has never been a real good film about the Balkan war.
The story of the three American war reporters, who set out to track down the top war criminal "the fox", could perhaps have become, with another director and another screenwriter (both at the same time Richard Shepard), at another time a new "Apocalypse Now".
Because the stories are strikingly similar: two males go on a small team in the forest, to accomplish something that the military can’t do and for both males, it becomes a journey into madness.
One of the reasons for the failure of "The Hunting Party" is that we simply don't let Simon Hunt be the cynical deserter with a heart, as he is presented to us at the beginning.
No, the script must also attribute to her a romantic adventure with a Bosniak murdered later.
Then "The Hunting Party" becomes definitively bad, when the reporter, in the last five minutes, through an accelerated process, achieves that NATO, the CIA and all the bounty hunters in the world have not succeeded in five years: catch the war criminal and leave him for a just revenge to the Muslim Bosniaks.
It is so bad that the International Court of Justice of the Hague should be seized of the crime against cinematographic logic.
In this case, the film has too deep a human preoccupation.
He wants to denounce that Karadzic and Mladic are still free, and he suspects the Americans and the French (here they must exceptionally agree) not to conduct the hunt in a rather intensive way because of secret political agreements.
But the good and the bad are so similar this time that a famous poem by Brecht comes to mind.
He talks about a wooden mask of an Asian demon on the poet's work table: "Compassionately, I see the veins of the forehead swollen, clearly: how tiring it is to be mean."
Movies like “The Hunting Party” have exactly such tumbling heads, but they hint at how tiring it is to be good.
The problem is not limited to the genre of films about the Balkan war.
Recently, it was reported in this newspaper that all Hollywood movies about Iraq were big flops.
We can add: there have never been any good films about South Africa.
Which is true every time: when a star is languishing on a crisis home or on a minefield, it then comes out something like "Rangoon" with Patricia Arquette, "Jenseits aller Grenzen" with Angelina Jolie or "Blutdiamanten" with Leonardo DiCaprio.
