These aren't Warhol's boxes.
He who connects the concepts of Sweden and wooden box, thinks of Ikea, but not Andy Warhol.
Or is it?
At the moment, wooden crates made in Sweden cast shadows on the list of works by Warhol.
A large part of the ninety Brillo-Boxes of "Type Stockholm" listed there are counterfeits.
After the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" questioned a few months ago the authenticity of the Brillo-Boxes of the year 1968 by Andy Warhol, the internal research of the Moderna Museet of Stockholm today results in a disenchanting result: the six "Brillo-Boxes", of which the former director of the Museum Pontus H.
Ancient history is intertwined, a bewildering chain of artistic and curatorial productions.
In 1964, Warhol created in New York his first "Brillo-Boxes", painted wooden cases, which are based on the red-blue-white design of the "Brillo" powder soap cartons.
An exhibition of his work at the Moderna Museet in 1968 - with the agreement of Warhol - presented hundreds of Brillo boxes made of cardboard: These did not come (for financial reasons) from Warhol, but had been delivered directly from the Brillo cardboard factory.
These were not works of art, but rather their models, samples of exhibition.
At the same time, Warhol had given permission in 1968 to produce some Brillo wooden boxes in Sweden, which were not on display at the Moderna Museet.
Eyewitnesses of the time speak today of about fifteen wooden boxes that at the time would have entered the history of art and auctions, as the original Brillo-Boxes of Andy Warhol allowed, with the name "Type Stockholm".
Some of them have raised more than $100,000 in auctions.
The problem now is that the legendary director of the Pontus Hultén Museum claimed, wrongly, later that about a hundred wooden cases had been produced and exhibited in Sweden in 1968, that Warhol would then have sold it to him.
In truth, Hultén’s 105 crates were produced in Malm<0xC3><0xB6> in 1990 only, for an exhibition in St. Petersburg.
By that date, Warhol had already been dead for three years.
Lars Bystr<0xC3><0xB6>m, Chief Curator of the Moderna Museet, examined, alongside the museum’s six Brillo-Boxes, three other Swedish private collections, two of which were made in Stockholm in 1968: their laminated panels were first printed and sanded, then applied with a paint brush.
The texture of the copies dating from the year 1990, on the contrary, reveals that the paint was applied directly without a background layer on the laminated panels, using a paint roller - moreover, it is not an oil painting, but an acrylic.
"These boxes were not authorized by the artist and should be removed from the official list of Andy Warhol's Brillo-Boxes," says the director of the Moderna Museet, Lars Nittve: "If the 'Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board' in New York does not come up with another decision, so much so that Moderna Muse will collect them."
Already in July, the Authentication Board announced, of course, that it would investigate the “heavy charges” that will be raised in the case of powdered soap cases.
But since then, there has been an inexorable silence.
The rebel soldiers of Manila are leaving.
In the Philippines, the rebel soldiers are abandoning, the same ones who had severed themselves in a hotel in Manila, and who had demanded the withdrawal of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo.
Chief Antonio Trillanes, who accused the President of corruption and electoral fraud, told reporters at the hotel that he could not answer for any bloodshed.
The loyal soldiers in power had stormed the hotel shortly before with tear gas.
The two dozen soldiers had been holed up in the building for hours.
About half of them were on Wednesday in front of the courts due to a failed coup attempt in 2003 - among them Trillanes.
He took advantage of the audience to suddenly eclipse himself with about 30 sympathizers.
The military police, who normally had to monitor them, had apparently deserted in his favor and had joined his mutiny.
They entered the Peninsula Hotel and demanded the removal of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo.
The loyal troops in power closed the area around the respectable hotel.
The Chairperson convened an urgent meeting of the Security Cabinet.
National Security Adviser Norberto Gonzales condemned the actions of the soldiers.
“People are tired of it,” Trillanes said.
“We call on people to join us.”
General Danilo Lim, who previously commanded the elite unit of the Scouts Rangers, said other army units wanted to join the march soon.
Critics of the regime had called for a large demonstration against the President on Wednesday.
His government has been surrounded for months by accusations of corruption.
Manila's financial district was already the scene of the attempted mutiny of about 200 members of the army against Arroyo since 2003.
The insurgency broke out nearly 24 hours after the army refused to join.
Since 1986, there have been at least seven coup attempts against democratically elected governments in the Philippines.
